00:43:11.720 --> 00:43:18.320
Yeah, this is a problem that would happen in Vue as well,

00:43:19.380 --> 00:43:24.720
where as that state changes, as your application state changes,

00:43:25.520 --> 00:43:31.320
that populate function that defines your DOM runs on every single state change.

00:43:31.900 --> 00:43:33.620
Unless you can override that.

00:43:34.060 --> 00:43:39.280
Maybe there's state that isn't important and you can turn that off.

00:43:39.350 --> 00:43:40.300
But that's the default.

00:43:41.170 --> 00:43:45.100
And so what that means is every time that you have a state change,

00:43:45.690 --> 00:43:46.820
the DOM could be different.

00:43:47.580 --> 00:43:50.820
And if the DOM is different and it patches the DOM,

00:43:51.760 --> 00:43:55.540
that means that the browser might have,

00:43:56.650 --> 00:44:01.100
let's say you're typing in an input element and the input element moves.

00:44:02.540 --> 00:44:04.920
you would lose focus on that element.

00:44:05.940 --> 00:44:09.100
And that's the example that you see in this demo.

00:44:10.060 --> 00:44:13.120
So if you give it a ref, that does two things.

00:44:14.120 --> 00:44:16.860
One, it identifies within that component.

00:44:16.970 --> 00:44:19.800
It's kind of like an ID, but it's local to the component.

00:44:20.040 --> 00:44:21.860
It's not a document-wide ID.

00:44:23.440 --> 00:44:28.160
It identifies it so that when it comes time to patch the DOM,

00:44:28.580 --> 00:44:34.080
it will reuse that HTML tag, that element in the DOM,

00:44:35.539 --> 00:44:40.200
and only update the attributes on it and the elements around it.

00:44:41.060 --> 00:44:45.960
So you get ultimately a smoother browser experience

00:44:46.660 --> 00:44:51.500
because it's being a little more intelligent about how it wants to patch the DOM.

00:44:52.620 --> 00:44:54.280
Right. So in your example, there's an input.

00:44:54.660 --> 00:45:09.260
And as you start typing into it with the naive or straightforward way, the thing reruns, but it regenerates the DOM in a way that completely blasts away that text input.

00:45:10.620 --> 00:45:17.460
It puts it back, but as you type, now all of a sudden it goes click, click, click, or beep, beep, beep, because it's no longer focused on there.

00:45:17.900 --> 00:45:19.160
Because that's not actually the same text box.

00:45:19.400 --> 00:45:21.400
It's a new one with the same value, right?

00:45:21.920 --> 00:45:27.280
And so in order to say, no, this thing is permanent, leave it here, don't recreate it for whatever reason.

